## RULE 2 — xssReflected.js

FILE: backend/src/scan/modules/xssReflected.js

PURPOSE: Test every URL parameter for reflected XSS by injecting payloads and checking if they appear unescaped in the response HTML.

IMPLEMENTATION RULES:
- For every node with URL parameters, inject each XSS payload into each parameter via GET request.
- Payloads to test:
  <script>alert('xss')</script>
  <img src=x onerror=alert(1)>
  "><svg onload=alert(1)>
  javascript:alert(1)
- After each request, check the response body for the EXACT payload string appearing unescaped.
  Unescaped means: the raw payload appears in the HTML without HTML entity encoding.
  Check specifically: the `<`, `>`, and `"` characters are NOT encoded as &lt; &gt; &quot;
- If the raw payload is found in the response body: it is a confirmed reflected XSS.
- Finding severity: "high"
- Finding object fields:
  title: "Reflected Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)"
  type: "xss"
  severity: "high"
  url: full tested URL
  method: "GET"
  parameter: vulnerable param name
  payload: the payload that reflected
  evidence: 300-char window of response body around where payload was found
  description: "The application reflects user-supplied input in the HTML response without proper encoding. An attacker can inject malicious scripts that execute in the victim's browser."
- Also check response Content-Type. If Content-Type is application/json and payload reflects, downgrade to "medium" (JSON responses are less directly exploitable for XSS).
- Export: module.exports = async function runXssReflected(scanId, nodes, scanConfig, db)

