## RULE 6 — rbacTester.js

FILE: backend/src/scan/modules/rbacTester.js

PURPOSE: Test for RBAC (role-based access control) failures by replaying requests with tokens from different roles and detecting unauthorized access.

IMPLEMENTATION RULES:
- Requires: scanConfig.roles array to have at least 2 role entries. If less than 2 roles, skip entirely and return [].
- Step 1: Crawl the target using the FIRST role (highest privilege, e.g. Admin). Collect all URLs that returned HTTP 200.
- Step 2: For each URL collected, replay the request using the SECOND role's token (lower privilege, e.g. Authenticated User).
  - If second role returns 200 → this might be a valid shared resource, check further.
  - If second role returns 200 AND the first role URL contains keywords like: admin, manage, dashboard, config, settings, user, account, delete, update, create, panel → flag as RBAC violation.
- Step 3: Also replay with NO token (unauthenticated) for any URL containing admin/manage keywords.
  - If unauthenticated request returns 200 → flag as critical RBAC violation.
- For each violation:
  Finding object:
  title: "Broken Access Control — Unauthorized Role Access" (or "Unauthenticated Access" if no token worked)
  type: "rbac"
  severity: "critical" (if unauthenticated) or "high" (if wrong role)
  url: the accessed URL
  method: "GET"
  parameter: "Authorization header / role token"
  payload: "Role: [role name used] — Token: [first 10 chars of token]..."
  evidence: "HTTP [status] returned for [role name]. Expected 403 or 401."
  description: "The endpoint [url] is accessible by [role] but should be restricted. This indicates a broken access control vulnerability where role boundaries are not enforced server-side."
- Build role headers:
  If role has token field: use Authorization: Bearer [token]
  If role has cookies field: use Cookie: [cookies]
- Export: module.exports = async function runRbacTester(scanId, nodes, scanConfig, db)

